         <abstract>
            <p>We examine the empirical determinants of debt maturity structure using a maturity structure measure that incorporates detailed information about all of a firm's liabilities. We find that larger, less risky firms with longer-term asset maturities use longer-term debt. Additionally, debt maturity varies inversely with earnings surprises and a firm's effective tax rate, but there is only mixed support for an inverse relation with growth opportunities. We find strong support for the prediction of a nonmonotonic relation between debt maturity and bond rating; firms with high or very low bond ratings use shorter-term debt.</p>
         </abstract>
